AGI - Aung San Suu Kyi, former head of the Burmese government and Nobel Peace Prize left the cell in which it was locked up by the coup of 2021 and was transferred to a house where it will receive special care for the excessively hot climate. To give the announcement was the spokesman of the military junta in power in Myanmar, Zaw Min Tun, on the occasion of the New Year. At the same time, he specified the same source, the grace was granted to 3,300 prisoners while other prisoners will benefit from a reduction of one-sixth of the penalty, except for the condemned for murder, terrorism and drug trafficking. The military junta spokesman also reported that the authorities adopted measures to protect vulnerable prisoners, including the 78-year-old historical leader Suu Kyi and former president U Win Myint, along with "some old prisoners who received the necessary care due to the very hot weather". However, with regard to Suu Kyi, the same source did not specify whether it is house arrest or penalty reduction and whether the measure is definitive or temporary.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
The local media recalled that during the process lasted months, Suu Kyi had suffered on several occasions of dizziness, had vomited and sometimes had not been able to eat because of a tooth infection. So far the army and its spokesmen have always denied the presence of any disease, failing, however, to dissipate discussions and speculations on the precarious state of health of the excellent prisoner. Two months ago, his son, Kim Aris, 47 years old, by telephone from London, told the media that his mother was still held in a complex specifically built in the military capital Naypyidaw.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
In a missive, the former head of government of Burmese, had written to the son for the first time, ensuring that "being well and maintaining high morality as ever". That letter was in fact the first tangible proof that the historic Burmese leader was actually alive. Suu Kyi was deposed and arrested on the morning of the military coup on 1 February 2021. Since then it has been sentenced to 33 years of imprisonment in defined processes a farce by human rights associations. The human rights activist, who has always stood in opposition to the military regime, awarded the Nobel Peace Prize in 1991, was found guilty of inciting the population against the military forces and some violations of Covid's conflict measures.
&nbsp;
Last year, on the occasion of Buddhist Lent, Suu Kyi received the grace for five of the 19 convicts, reducing his sentence of several years. Since three years ago the army has overthrown the democratically elected government, Myanmar is preying to an internal rebellion, which in recent months has inflicted heavy defeats on the armed forces and conquered large portions of the territory. For the local Association of assistance to political prisoners (AAPP), there are over 4,800 victims of military repression and over 25 thousand arrested people. &nbsp;
