AGI - Turkish President Recep Tayyip Erdogan confirmed the next visit to Turkey by Russian President Vladimir Putin and remains at the forefront to mediate in the dispute that sees oppositions Hamas and the Iranian regime against Israel and the United States, to avoid an expansion of the conflict in the Middle East. Putin's visit, initially announced for last February and then postponed, should take place presumably in the first part of May. Erdogan will speak with the Russian leader of the situation in Gaza >, but above all of the war in Ukraine.
&nbsp;
In the face-to-face with the Russian president is primary interest of Erdogan trying to convince Putin to share the agreement concerning the 'wheat corridor'. An agreement reached between Kiev and Moscow in July 2022 with the mediation of Turkey, which allowed the safe passage through the Black Sea of hundreds of thousands tons of wheat and food blocked by war in the Ukrainian ports. Agreement jumped in May 2023 by Moscow will. Russia wants in fact that the passage of its products and fertilizers is guaranteed, as originally foreseen by the agreement. Erdogan recently raised Turkey's willingness to host a peace summit. On the margin of the recent visit to Istanbul by Ukrainian President Volodimir Zelensky, Erdogan said that "Turkey is ready to mediate" > and pushes for a political solution to the conflict. "We are ready to restart and host a negotiation that leads to peace, as we did in Istanbul (March 2022 ndr)", said the Turkish leader.
&nbsp;
Erdogan from the beginning of the conflict maintained a balanced position that allowed him to attempt mediation between Moscow and Kiev. While not failing NATO's commitments and condemning the invasion, the Turkish President did not apply sanctions, he held open channels with Moscow and now awaits Putin in Ankara. The two met last time in Sochi, Russia, last August. Compared to the Middle East conflict both countries maintain an open channel with the leaders of the Hamas Palestinian organization. While Erdogan was distinguished by the fierce criticism of the Jewish state, Russia took net positions at the UN Security Council and asked, as well as the Turkish leader, repeatedly a ceasefire.
&nbsp;
<div </div
<h2> Russia and Turkey
Iranian president Ebrahim Raisi was in Ankara from Erdogan last month, while Tehran to Russia provides drones that are then used in Ukraine. Both Russia and Turkey have asked Iran to avoid acts that could lead to an expansion of the conflict and jeopardize the stability of the area.&nbsp; Erdogan is hosting some Hamas leaders abroad in Turkey, with a strong influence on the Palestinian organization, but does not dialogue with Israel. However, it is important to remember that last 12 April the US Secretary of State, Anthony Blinken, asked Turkish Foreign Minister Hakan Fidan to mediate with Iran in order to avoid attacks on Israeli targets. A request that the United States, after the Iranian attack on 13 April, sent to Ankara also through the CIA during a call between William Burns, number one of the U.S. intelligence and the head of Turkish services, Ibrahim Kalin.
&nbsp;
According to the report, following the dialogue with Burns, the head of Turkish intelligence had a telephone conversation with Hamas representatives. The Turkish leader, expected to the White House on 9 May next found himself, once again, in a privileged position. The conflict between Israel and Hamas has contributed to bringing Turkey and Iran closer together. The United States knows that in case of war with Iran Turkey will deny the use of its military bases, a script already seen with Iraq in the past. To offer itself as a basis for attacking another Muslim country is in Turkey a real political suicide >.
&nbsp;
The White House prefers to focus on the influence that Erdogan has on Hamas and Tehran, but also on the need of the Turkish leader to try any way to avoid its country from an enlargement of the conflict to the whole region. The Turkish president wants to prevent the conflict from spreading to its own borders and to contain the reaction of the Lebanese Hezbollahs, the Iranian militias in Syria and Iraq and the ayatollahs themselves are forced to intensify the pressing on Tehran. Consolidating relations with Erdogan would allow Tehran to have an intermediary with the United States, avoid new heavy sanctions and alleviate an isolation that squeezes the population, annihilates diplomacy and pushes the country towards war.&nbsp;&nbsp;
&nbsp;
